# Plan format for reviewable documents

Any document intended for the user to read, review, or act on — plans, checklists, coordination files, verification guides, private trackers — must use the Cursor plan format:

```yaml
---
name: Short human-readable title
overview: "One sentence describing the purpose and scope of this document."
todos:
  - id: unique-kebab-id
    content: "Actionable item the user or agent needs to complete"
    status: pending   # pending | in_progress | completed | cancelled
isProject: false
---
```

Followed by standard Markdown content.

## Rules

- Always include `name`, `overview`, `todos` (at least one), and `isProject: false`.
- Each todo maps to a concrete action — W1/W2/W3 workstream steps, checklist items, verification checks.
- Plain Markdown without frontmatter is only acceptable for auto-generated output (scorecards, raw results).
- Files that are **not** for the user to review (e.g. `AGENT_HANDOVER.md`, `PROJECT_STATE.md`) are exempt.

## File location

| Use case | Location | Extension |
|----------|----------|-----------|
| Coordination plan, verification, audit, private tracker (one consolidated file) | `/Users/jglover/.cursor/plans/` | `.plan.md` |
| Public-facing doc | Repo `docs/` | `.md` (no frontmatter needed) |

`~/.cursor/plans/` lives outside any git repo, so private content (IPs, ARNs, tickets, secrets) is safe there. Use a single `.plan.md` per topic — coordination + tracker in one file.

**Never** put a reviewable plan in `docs/` (gitignored or otherwise) — it will not render interactively in Cursor. Always use `.cursor/plans/*.plan.md`.
